    "answer_id" : 2154340,
    "question_id" : 2154251,
    "content_license" : "CC BY-SA 4.0",
    "body" : "<p>A default value of 0 for arrays of integral types is guaranteed by the <a href=\"http://docs.oracle.com/javase/specs/jls/se7/html/jls-4.html#jls-4.12.5\" rel=\"noreferrer\">language spec</a>:</p>\n\n<blockquote>\n  <p>Each class variable, instance variable, or array component is initialized with a <em>default value</em> when it is created (§15.9, §15.10) [...] For type <code>int</code>, the default value is zero, that is, <code>0</code>. &nbsp;</p>\n</blockquote>\n\n<p>If you want to initialize an one-dimensional array to a different value, you can use <a href=\"http://java.sun.com/javase/6/docs/api/java/util/Arrays.html#fill(int[],%20int)\" rel=\"noreferrer\">java.util.Arrays.fill()</a> (which will of course use a loop internally).</p>\n"
  }, {
