    "body" : "<p>declare the array as instance variable in the class i.e. out of every method and JVM will give it 0 as default value. You need not to worry anymore  </p>\n"
  }, {
    "comments" : [ {
      "owner" : {
        "account_id" : 132773,
        "reputation" : 1358,
        "user_id" : 333675,
        "user_type" : "registered",
        "profile_image" : "https://www.gravatar.com/avatar/f07f95af36b78a8d151b42218fe8d1b4?s=256&d=identicon&r=PG",
        "display_name" : "Ian Robertson",
        "link" : "https://stackoverflow.com/users/333675/ian-robertson"
      },
      "edited" : false,
      "score" : 0,
      "creation_date" : 1470873849,
      "post_id" : 36489990,
      "comment_id" : 65131335,
      "content_license" : "CC BY-SA 3.0",
      "body" : "According to the Java Language specification, section <a href=\"https://docs.oracle.com/javase/specs/jls/se8/html/jls-15.html#jls-15.10.2\" rel=\"nofollow noreferrer\">15.10.2</a>, if an array is created with an array creation exception that does not provide initial values, then all the elements of the array are initialized to the default value for the array&#39;s component type - i.e. 0 in the case of char[]. This is a guarantee; I&#39;d be quite surprised of Oracle considered relying on it to be a bad practice."
    } ],
